article.headline: Gophers break school scoring record in rout
article.linkText: Borton wins debut as No. 17 Minnesota pounds IPFW
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Her team set a school scoring record, but
Minnesota coach Pam Borton saw one area in which the Golden Gophers
could improve: defense.

	   Lindsay Whalen had 23 points and nine assists and Corrin Von
Wald added 21 points Saturday as (No. 17 ESPN/USA Today, No. 16 AP) Minnesota set a school
record in a 116-73 win over Indiana-Purdue-Fort Wayne in the Subway
Basketball Classic.

	   "We can still score a lot of points,'' Borton said, "but we
don't know if we can play any defense yet.''

   Minnesota will face Radford in the championship game Sunday.
Radford beat Savannah State 86-57.

	   Kadidja Andersson had 17 points and 10 rebounds and Kim Prince
added 16 points for the Gophers (1-0), who broke the previous
scoring record of 115 points, set in March 1983 against Purdue.

	   Borton replaced Brenda Oldfield (now known by her maiden name,
Frese), the national coach of the year in her lone season at
Minnesota, who's now at Maryland.

	   The Gophers (1-0) allowed an average of more than 71 points last
season, and Borton's first priority is to get the team playing
effective man-to-man pressure defense.

	   "It's a work in progress,'' said Whalen, the Big Ten Player of
the Year last season.

	   Minnesota held the Mastodons (0-1) without a point for the first
four minutes, but the Gophers seemed soft in some stretches.
Indiana-Purdue-Fort Wayne had 20 offensive rebounds.

	   "The players were talking about it on the bench,'' Von Wald
said. "Once we got to 112, we were like, 'Let's get a bucket.
Let's get a bucket.' It's a great accomplishment, but we have to
look back on our defense. It's a little frustrating from the
players' standpoint.''

	   Amy Gearlds scored 18 points, Lindy Carey had 17 and Hillary
O'Connell 12 for the Mastodons, who have only three players back
from last year's 4-23 team and are playing in Division I for the
first time. They've got eight freshman on the roster.

	   "We're a very young basketball team trying to learn to play,''
coach Bruce Patterson said. "I really appreciate coach (Borton)
not paying us an insult by backing off. We wanted to battle right
up to the end.''

	   The Gophers, who return all five starters and 95 percent of
their scoring from last year's 22-8 team, outscored the Mastodons
49-2 on fastbreak points.

		   The Gophers, who have moved permanently from the Sports Pavilion
next door to Williams Arena where the men's team plays, won't get
much of a test until the Big Ten season starts.

	   The remainder of their nonconference schedule includes Loyola of
Chicago, Providence, Harvard, Missouri-Kansas City, Northern Iowa,
Wright State, Dayton and a holiday tournament with Air Force, New
Orleans and Winthrop.
